This was sent to me by the ever-wise and worldly Mark T, when I lamented about how  La Guarida Cubana was gone and replaced by this place:

&#34;At the moment Los Parceros is only open Saturdays and Sundays - they are still in soft-opening mode. Certainly recommended all the same =) &#34;

This would explain why it was closed at 5:15 on a Thursday night last week (but there were still people inside, watching a small TV perched high above their heads).  Anyways, this isn&#39;t a legit review; more of a useful piece of info if anyone comes by to try them out.  Nuke it if you need to. Cheers.

So I&#39;ve never heard of this place before, but stumbled upon it after giving a lady a ride from downtown. I figured, &#34;Hey, why not?&#34;
It&#39;s a small place with an Indy feel, but don&#39;t let that fool ya! This place needs an angelic host surrounding it, leading the lost and hungry inside! I&#39;m talking full-on singing, saving, shining messengers of God leading people to salvation from hunger, man! I had the Scarpone on suggestion from the waitress and let me tell you: one bite, and it was impossible to pry that burger from my grasp! It was like a food-gasm!
I can&#39;t wait to be hungry again so I can go back!

If you&#39;re catching a game, they&#39;ve got plenty of flat screens in ever corner. The bar is a beautifully carved, dark wood piece that recalls literally the Prohibition days, however the rest of the space doesn&#39;t seem to aesthetically align with the old-time look the name might suggest. On the other hand, the crowd is a good mix of laid back and fun-loving people. 

On Sundays, the brunch boast $10 carafes of Mimosas and Bloody Marys, plus the draft specials aren&#39;t too shabby either. The Kitchen Sink Salad satiated me for a bit, but I really wish the ingredients could have been more frequent. That and the server. Very polite but a little inconsistent until it was time to take our credit card. The place wasn&#39;t packed. In the case of an over pouring of people, I would&#39;ve understood the slower service. 

I definitely would come back to to Prohibition for the Sunday brunch and possibly a heartier meal. This place is fun and evokes a &#39;neighborhood&#39; vibe where &#39;everyone knows your name.&#39;

Decided to brunch at Atticus while I was in town and wanting to catch up with good friends. I guess it should have been a sign when the place was empty at 10:30 am during brunch on a Sunday. The food was nothing special, didn&#39;t come out hot but it wasn&#39;t worth complaining about. I had a girlfriend order the huevos rancheros and the menu said it came with a side of corn tortillas. It didn&#39;t come out with any corn tortillas so she ask the waitress. The waitress was extremely rude. Her name was Jennifer. Also the bar tender I believe. She argued with my friend saying she read the menu wrong. Then to prove my friend was wrong, went and got the menu only to read that it did indeed come with corn tortillas on the side in addition to the single street taco sized corn tortilla that was on the dish. Brought out an additional two corn tortillas and said &#34;who needs these anyways&#34; service lacked in every way from that moment forward. 
Didn&#39;t refill water or coffee. Brought our checks super early when we probably would have had another couple mimosas while chatting. 
My friend stood up to calm
Her baby and this waitress came up behind her and rudely said excuse me. I guess the first time my friend didn&#39;t hear her. My friend commented that she was rude and that she didn&#39;t hear her. And the waitress &#34;Jennifer&#34; replied &#34;you guys are rude&#34; walked away and called us bitches. I was appalled. For an empty restaurant during Sunday brunch time. This place can&#39;t afford a waitress like her. We also heard her be rude to another table. A question was asked and she responded &#34;is that real question&#34; 
Truly rude. Jennifer, I think you&#39;re in the wrong industry. 
Please note that we are all women, married, with children wanting to enjoy brunch and catch up. We were not rude. The server was rude from the time we sat down which put us all on edge. We did expect good, courteous, respectful service. We did nothing to warrant being called &#34;bitches&#34;

Lunch time bummer . . . we love eating here (live or take-out) for dinner but went in for lunch this week and, yikes! We called ahead, were told our order would be ready just after 1 and then waited, waited, waited . . . along about 1:25 we said something and then there was a scurry as servers grabbed some of our items off of the buffet line (and that meant one of our items was cold and not spiced as we ordered it). Then we got home and discovered another of items had been substituted and wasn&#39;t what we ordered! When we called they said immediately (no pause or checking anything), &#34;No, you ordered wrong. Anyways, we gave you a thing of sauce so just mix it together and then it will be the same as what you ordered.&#34;

If we ordered wrong, why would they give us this sauce solution without our mentioning anything . . . Also, how do you have an answer for our &#34;wrong item&#34; all ready already, without checking the order or discussing it further? Finally, even if we DID order it wrong, this is a pretty not-service-oriented answer to give. UGH.

We&#39;ll never go back for lunch and we may take a break for awhile anyways. Too bad.

I&#39;m torn between 2 or 3 stars here because I really felt &#34;meh,&#34; but I&#39;d also be willing to give it a second chance. 

We had the beet salad and falafel sandwich for dinner and thought they were good, but just didn&#39;t hit the spot. We weren&#39;t hungry when we came home from dinner, but we were both feeling &#34;meh.&#34;

Like I said, the food was good and we&#39;d be willing to go back a second time, so maybe I&#39;ll feel differently after the next visit.

When you look at this place from the outside, you wouldn&#39;t think that it is a good as it is. The Dragon Boat is my uncle&#39;s favorite restaurant and has begged me to go there with him for years! I would pass by it almost everyday and say &#34;I&#39;ll go there one day.&#34; 

That day finally happened and I must say I was extremely impressed. Now I see why my uncle eats there 2-3 time a week. We ordered a full spread, lo mien, sushi, soup, etc. and it was all excellent. The staff was fun, I am sure part of that is because how often my uncle comes in and how much money he spends there as a regular. 

I can&#39;t say that I would be a regular here because it is pretty far from where I live, however; I can definitely say, when I am craving Chinese cuisine, I will definitely have the Dragon Boat at the top of my list!
